perceived France to be the core of a Western civilization whose leadership and values were threatened by Americanization, anti-imperial nationalism, and non-white immigration. By following Siegfried’s long career and examining the breadth of his writings, Sean Kennedy shows how his racial and ethnic essentialism was a unifying aspect of his life’s work. That these ideas were considered unremarkable for most of his lifetime offers a powerful illustration of how racist thinking permeated mainstream French republicanism.Exploring the many facets of Siegfried’s career, France in the World examines the entanglement of liberal and racist thinking during an era that witnessed political extremism and a rapidly changing international order.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIntellectualszFrancevBiography. 0aPolitical scientistszFrancevBiography. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  aAmericanization.  aAustralia.  aCanada.  aCatholicism.  aChina.  aEurope.  aFirst World War.  aFrench Fourth Republic.  aFrench Third Republic.  aGreat Britain.  aJapan.  aJules.  aJulie Siegfried.  aKorea.  aLatin America.  aMusée Social.  aNew Zealand.  aPhilippines.  aProtestantism.  aSciences Po.  aSecond World War.  aSouth Africa.  aSouth Asia.  aUnited States.  aWestern Civilization.  acapitalism.  aclericalism.  acolonialism.  acommunism.  aconservatism.  aeconomics.  aelectoral geography.  aimperialism.  aliberalism.  amodernity.  apolitical science.  aracism.  areligion.  arepublicanism.  asocialism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228015338?